Question: Which of the following is a correctly written chemical equation that demonstrates the conservation of mass?
Options:
A. Mg + HCl -> H_{2} + MgCl_{2}
B. H_{2}O + CO_{2} -> H_{2}CO_{3}
C. KClO_{3} -> KCl + O_{2}
D. H_{2} + O_{2} -> H_{2}O
Answer:

A. Mg + HCl -> H_{2} + MgCl_{2}
This equation does not demonstrate the conservation of mass because the number of atoms on the left side of the equation (1 Mg, 1 H, 1 Cl) is not equal to the number of atoms on the right side of the equation (2 H, 1 Mg, 2 Cl).

B. H_{2}O + CO_{2} -> H_{2}CO_{3}
This equation does not demonstrate the conservation of mass because the number of atoms on the left side of the equation (2 H, 1 C, 3 O) is not equal to the number of atoms on the right side of the equation (2 H, 1 C, 4 O).

C. KClO_{3} -> KCl + O_{2}
This equation does demonstrate the conservation of mass because the number of atoms on the left side of the equation (1 K, 1 Cl, 3 O) is equal to the number of atoms on the right side of the equation (1 K, 1 Cl, 3 O).

D. H_{2} + O_{2} -> H_{2}O
This equation does demonstrate the conservation of mass because the number of atoms on the left side of the equation (2 H, 2 O) is equal to the number of atoms on the right side of the equation (2 H, 2 O).

Therefore, the correct answer is D. H_{2} + O_{2} -> H_{2}O.

